Project description:
This project will assist Alexander Health Services to:
1. Build capacity through the education sessions/workshops, information sharing providing new tools/knowledge/methods to increase the ability to better understand and manage the health impacts of climate change to Alexander First Nation.
2. Through supplying Earth Boxes to the Elders Lodge, Boys Home and the school, the most vulnerable part of the population learns how to be more self-sufficient by  growing vegetables, they have a greater sense of being part of the community by being involved in the project and they are making their own contribution to sustainability in food security.
3. Develop sustainability by learning and practicing techniques and knowledge gained through workshops/educational sessions/gatherings and utilizing the successful participants at future engagements, planning sessions and gatherings.
4. Improve health and wellness by improving access to more nutritious food sources and encouraging healthy eating;
5. Improve communications and the sense of belonging to their community - encouraging the sharing of skills, techniques and knowledge at all gatherings, workshops and educational sessions;
6. Utilize the Elders and knowledge keepers to help identify the various species of plant products needed for the practice of the traditions and cultural ceremonies of the nation;
7. Involve the youth in learning and practicing the traditions and culture of hunting, trapping and fishing.

This project helps: 
• mapping terrain stability on a combination of remote sensing and Inuit knowledge;
• developing an archaeology module;
• using the vulnerability and risk assessments to intervene in saving Inuit heritage through salvage archaeology;
• recording Inuinnait knowledge on climate change;
• providing employement for youth and transferring knowledge  from engaging with Elders and professional archaeologists.

Description du projet:
Ce projet aide à : 
• cartographier l’état de stabilité du terrain en combinant la télédétection et les connaissances inuites;
• élaborer un module archéologique;
• utiliser les évaluations de la vulnérabilité et des risques pour intervenir dans la sauvegarde du patrimoine inuit grâce à l’archéologie de préservation;
• enregistrer les connaissances des Inuinnait sur les changements climatiques;
• fournir des emplois aux jeunes et transférer les connaissances acquises grâce à leur engagement auprès des aînés et d’archéologues professionnels.
